---
import "../styles/global.css";

const ssrnUrl =
  "https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=5984574";
---

<!doctype html>

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />

    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
    />

    <title>
      The Theorem of Minimal Tolerance
    </title>

    <meta
      name="description"
      content="The Theorem of Minimal Tolerance examines when an institution that is morally illegitimate and functionally inefficient may nevertheless be tolerated as an institutional technology of last resort."
    />
  </head>

  <body>

    <header class="site-header">

      <a href="/" class="logo">
        The Theorem of Minimal Tolerance
      </a>

      <nav aria-label="Main navigation">
        <a href="#theory">Theory</a>
        <a href="#theorem">Theorem</a>
        <a href="#book">Book</a>
        <a href="#paper">Paper</a>
        <a href="#author">Author</a>
      </nav>

    </header>

    <main>

      <section class="hero">

        <div class="hero-content">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            POWER, COERCION AND POLITICAL AUTHORITY
          </p>

          <h1>
            Minimal Tolerance
            <span>The Theorem of the Last Resort</span>
          </h1>

          <p class="lead">
            The State is neither morally legitimate nor
            functionally efficient.
          </p>

          <div class="animated-text">
            <span>Why, then, is any State tolerated at all?</span>
            <span>Any exception requires proof.</span>
            <span>The burden of proof belongs to power.</span>
          </div>

          <div class="buttons">

            <a href="#theory" class="primary">
              Explore the Theory
            </a>

            <a href="#paper" class="secondary">
              Read the Paper
            </a>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          The question is not whether the State is desirable.
          It is not. The question is where to draw a boundary
          that does not undermine the principle itself.
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <section id="theory" class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            WHAT IS MINIMAL TOLERANCE?
          </p>

          <h2>
            From legitimacy to tolerance
          </h2>

          <p>
            The Theorem of Minimal Tolerance begins from two
            conclusions. First, the State lacks intrinsic moral
            legitimacy because taxation and political authority
            ultimately depend on coercion rather than consent.
            Second, state action suffers from structural
            information and economic-calculation problems.
          </p>

          <p>
            If the State is neither morally legitimate nor
            generally efficient, intervention cannot be presumed
            justified. The burden of proof must rest entirely
            with those proposing coercion.
          </p>

          <p>
            Minimal Tolerance therefore asks a narrower question:
            under what exceptional conditions may an institution
            that remains illegitimate and functionally flawed
            nevertheless be tolerated?
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE CORE ARGUMENT
          </p>

          <h2>
            Market imperfection is not enough
          </h2>

          <p>
            Frictions, externalities, imperfect outcomes and
            coordination difficulties do not automatically justify
            coercion. Markets need not be perfect for state
            intervention to remain unjustified.
          </p>

          <p>
            The relevant comparison is not between an imperfect
            market and an ideal State. It is between voluntary
            arrangements capable of adaptation and a coercive
            institution affected by dispersed knowledge,
            calculation problems and weak mechanisms of correction.
          </p>

          <p>
            The existence of a social problem does not establish
            that coercion is the appropriate response.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            A NARROW EXCEPTION
          </p>

          <h2>
            The structural free-rider problem
          </h2>

          <p>
            The theory identifies one narrow category of cases in
            which limited tolerance may be considered: structural
            free-rider problems in which voluntary provision
            persistently collapses because of the incentive
            structure itself.
          </p>

          <p>
            This is not a general theory of market failure.
            It does not apply merely because a good is useful,
            socially important or imperfectly supplied.
          </p>

          <p>
            The exception exists only when voluntary provision
            remains unviable under an exceptionally high
            evidentiary standard.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section id="theorem" class="theorem">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE FORMAL TEST
          </p>

          <h2>
            The Minimal Tolerance Theorem
          </h2>

          <p>
            A structural free-rider problem exists only when
            three conditions are simultaneously satisfied:
          </p>

          <div class="theorem-conditions">

            <article>
              <span>01</span>
              <h3>Effective non-excludability</h3>
              <p>
                Individuals cannot be effectively excluded from
                receiving the relevant benefit.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <span>02</span>
              <h3>Relevant non-rivalry</h3>
              <p>
                One person receiving the benefit does not
                meaningfully reduce its availability to others.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <span>03</span>
              <h3>Persistent voluntary collapse</h3>
              <p>
                Stable voluntary provision remains unviable and
                the failure cannot be attributed to removable
                regulatory obstacles.
              </p>
            </article>

          </div>

          <img
            src="/images/theorem.png"
            alt="Diagram of the Minimal Tolerance Theorem"
            loading="lazy"
          />

        </div>

      </section>

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          The State may be tolerated only as an institutional
          technology of last resort.
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE BURDEN OF PROOF
          </p>

          <h2>
            No presumption. No analogical expansion.
          </h2>

          <p>
            Tolerance may be considered only when non-intervention
            would generate greater harm than the marginal harm
            introduced by state coercion.
          </p>

          <p>
            The burden of proof lies entirely with those proposing
            intervention. The exception cannot be presumed,
            generalized or expanded by analogy.
          </p>

          <p>
            Where no structural free-rider problem exists, or where
            viable voluntary mechanisms remain available, state
            intervention lacks functional justification.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section id="book" class="book">

        <div class="container">

          <div class="book-grid">

            <div>

              <img
                src="/images/book-cover.jpg"
                alt="Cover of Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy by Federico Rodrigo"
                loading="lazy"
              />

            </div>

            <div>

              <p class="eyebrow">
                THE BOOK
              </p>

              <h2>
                Power, Tolerance and Legitimacy
              </h2>

              <p>
                A book-length examination of coercion, political
                authority, public goods, free riders, economic
                calculation and the institutional limits of power.
              </p>

              <p>
                The book develops the moral, economic and
                institutional arguments that culminate in the
                Theorem of Minimal Tolerance.
              </p>

            </div>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section id="paper" class="ssrn">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            SSRN PREPRINT
          </p>

          <h2>
            Read the Foundational Paper
          </h2>

          <p>
            Read the formal statement of the theorem, the argument
            concerning structural free-rider problems, and the
            exceptionally narrow conditions under which state
            coercion may be tolerated.
          </p>

          <a
            href={ssrnUrl}
            class="primary"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            Open on SSRN
          </a>

        </div>

      </section>

      <section id="author" class="content-section author">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE AUTHOR
          </p>

          <h2>
            Federico Rodrigo
          </h2>

          <p>
            Federico Rodrigo is an independent author and essayist.
            His work examines coercion, political authority,
            institutional incentives and the limits of state power.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

    </main>

    <footer>

      <p>
        © 2026 Minimal Tolerance · Federico Rodrigo
      </p>

